\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Definition
Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, a 
\series bold
binary relation
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, is a subset of ordered pairs of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\subseteq X\times X.
\]

\end_inset

 We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)\in R$
\end_inset

 or, equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relations can be expressed as directed graphs.
 For instance, a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be represented as the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{R}=\left(N_{X},E_{R}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{X}$
\end_inset

 are the nodes, representing each element in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{R}$
\end_inset

 are the edges, representing each pair in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The edges are constructed in such a way that 
\begin_inset Formula $e=\left(x,y\right)\in E_{R}\iff xRy$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left\{ a,b,c,d\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left\{ \left(a,b\right),\left(a,c\right),\left(b,d\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

, then we can represent this by 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{R}$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
