\begin_layout Standard
In addition, we can define paths and cycles on relations, analogously as
 how it is done in graph theory:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\series bold
path
\series default
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

 exists if there are 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},...,x_{n}\in X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=x_{1}Rx_{2}R\dots Rx_{n-1}Rx_{n}=y.
\]

\end_inset

 A path is called a 
\series bold
cycle
\series default
 if the it goes from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For every relation, we can extract two subrelations, as its symmetric part
 and its asymmetric part:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Definition
Given a binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can define its 
\series bold
symmetric part
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xIy\iff\left[xRy\land yRx\right],
\]

\end_inset

 and its 
\series bold
asymmetric part
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xPy\iff\left[xRy\land not\left(yRx\right)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symmetric part is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 because we can understand this as the all the indiferent pairs of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In others words, if we understand a relation as a preference over the elements
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 would mean 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is at least as convenient as 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 Therefore, if we have 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

, we could think of them as equally convenient, so the decision between
 them is indiferent.
 On the other hand, the asymmetric part is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, from preference, following a similar reasoning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we have two different relations, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

, on the same set, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We can define their concatenation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 be two relations on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define their 
\series bold
concatenation
\series default
 as
