\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of the numerical representation is to try to construct a binary
 relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

 on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that there exists a numerical function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the property
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\succsim y\iff f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right).
\]

\end_inset

 Therefore, we are trying to convey the information given by the relation
 via a mathematical function.
 When doing this, we usually assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 to be a preorder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also usually use the following notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y$
\end_inset

 means 
\emph on
x is at least as good as y
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is the asymmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is the symmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cantor proved a theorem that answered this problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Theorem
Cantor, 1895
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a countable set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

 a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\left[\exists f:X\rightarrow\mathbb{R}|\forall x,y\in X,x\succsim y\iff f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right)\right]\\
\Updownarrow\\
\succsim\ \text{is a complete preorder on }X.
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\implies\right]$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Completeness: pick 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

, then we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a linearly ordered set, it is either 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(y\right)\geq f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This, by hypothesis means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succsim x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Transitivity: pick 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succsim z$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(y\right)\geq f\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The transitivity in the real line gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

, which by hypothesis means 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

 is a complete preorder on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\impliedby\right]$
\end_inset

 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

 is a complete preorder on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is countable, we can enumerate its elements, i.e., we can express
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\left\{ x_{i}:i\in K\subset\mathbb{N}\right\} =\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},...\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(y\right)=\left\{ i\in K:y\succsim x_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

, i.e., the set of indices of elements put after 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cccc}
f: & X & \rightarrow & \mathbb{R}\\
 & y & \mapsto & f\left(y\right)=\sum_{i\in N\left(y\right)}\frac{1}{2^{i}}
\end{array}.
\]

\end_inset

 This series is convergent, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n\in\mathbb{N}}\frac{1}{2^{n}}=2$
\end_inset

 and we are taking a subset of it.
 Let's see that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y\iff f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y$
\end_inset

, then, the transitivity of the relation ensures that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\left(x\right)\supseteq N\left(y\right),
\]

\end_inset

 therefore, it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right),
\]

\end_inset

 simply because we are summing over more elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

 is complete, then it must be 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succsim x$
\end_inset

, which combined with 
\begin_inset Formula $not\left(x\succsim y\right)$
\end_inset

 gives us that it must be 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(y\right)\supsetneq N\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This means that there are elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 which are not in 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(y\right)>f\left(x\right)\#$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 Therefore, it must be 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succsim y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Note that this theorem ensures that such a function can only be found if
 the relation is a complete preorder, and therefore all partial preorders
 that are not complete cannot be assigned such a function.
 Note also that the defined function is not unique (for instance, add 1
 to this function, and it still works).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, the following proposition proves that even if there are infinite
 possible such functions, they are all related:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succsim$
\end_inset

 be a complete preorder on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, representable by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Then, the following two properties are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
