\begin_layout Standard
The objectives of this section are to study a set of decision problems in
 which a group has to take a decision among several alternatives and analyzing
 a number of properties of electoral systems.
 For this, we will present a few elements of the classical 
\series bold
social choice theory
\series default
, for which we will see that several parameters need to be taken into account.
 These are the nature of the decision, the size of the group and its nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Study election problems in which a society has to take a decision among
 several candidates.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When electing a candidate, we assume that the choice of the candidate will
 affect the member of society, and should therefore take the opinion of
 all members into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuition then is that a democratic approach is preferred, through an
 election system in which a candidate should be elected through some kind
 of majority rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, this approach has many political considerations, like if the
 democracy is direct or indirect, how parties play a role, who can vote,
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But there are also technical considerations involved in this problem.
 For instance, the definition of majority is obvious when there are two
 candidates: the candidate receiving more than half the votes is preferred
 to the other one.
 However, when there are more than two candidates, there are many ways to
 extend this simple idea, which are not equivalent and can lead to different
 and even unwanted results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, elections can by of different types:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Type of ballots admitted: only one candidate; or a ranking of all candidates;
 or all acceptable candidates; or grading candidates; etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Method for organizing the election and tallying ballots.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consequences of all this is that there are many possible types of elections,
 many of which have been proposed and even used in practice.
\end_layout

