\begin_layout Paragraph
Manipulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Manipulation occurs when some voters are not sincere, to improve the result
 of the election according to their preferences.
 Let's see this through an example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In the previous example, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 was elected.
 Howeber, suppose that the 6 voters with preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $c\succ a\succ d\succ b$
\end_inset

 vote as if their preferences were 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ c\succ d\succ b$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 would be elected in the first round with 11 votes.
 Therefore, it is profitable to the six manipulating voters, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Definition
A voting rule is 
\series bold
manipulable
\series default
 if it may happen that some voters may have an interest to vote in a non-sincere
 way.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have just seen with the previous example that plurality with runoff is
 manipulable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Monotonicity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monotonicity refers to a property of a voting method.
 It means that if a candidate increments its valoration for some population,
 the outcome of the election should not worsen for this candidate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider 3 candidates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a,b,c\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 17 voters, with the following distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
6\ voters: & a\succ b\succ c\\
5\ voters: & c\succ a\succ b\\
4\ voters: & b\succ c\succ a\\
2\ voters: & b\succ a\succ c
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 would be elected in the second round.
 However, imagine that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 now gets more money and can increase their campaign power.
 Through this campaign, they manage to change the preferences of the two
 last voters, effectively changing the distribution to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
8\ voters: & a\succ b\succ c\\
5\ voters: & c\succ a\succ b\\
4\ voters: & b\succ c\succ a
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is elected! The good campaign done by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, made him lose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this example, we observe that when the voting method is non-monotonic,
 the possibilities of manipulation increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Condorcet Voting Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Color Box
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Condorcet: rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compare all candidates by pair.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Declare that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is socially preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 if strictly more voters prefer 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Condorcet principle
\series default
: if one candidate is preferred to all other candidates, this one should
 be elected.
 This is the 
\series bold
Condorcet winner
\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The condorcet winner, if there is one, must be unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Plurality rule and plurality with runoff violate Condorcet's principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Condorcet's principle does not solve the 'dictature of the majority' difficulty.
 This is, a majority of the population only take their objectives into account.
 Since they are more, they can decide the elections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
A Condorcet winner is not necessarily ranked high by voters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider 3 candidates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a,b,c\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 21 voters, with the following distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
10\ voters: & a\succ b\succ c\\
6\ voters: & b\succ c\succ a\\
5\ voters: & c\succ b\succ a
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The results according to Condorcet are:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 but not to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the Condorcet winner.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider 4 candidates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a,b,c,d\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 21 voters, with the following distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
10\ voters: & b\succ a\succ c\succ d\\
6\ voters: & c\succ a\succ d\succ b\\
5\ voters: & a\succ d\succ b\succ c
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

