\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Condorcet's Paradox
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The social strict preference relation may have circuits:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider 3 candidates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a,b,c\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 3 voters, with the following distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1\ voter: & a\succ b\succ c\\
1\ voter: & b\succ c\succ a\\
1\ voter: & c\succ a\succ b
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, electing the Condorcet winner is an attractive idea, but not
 always possible or effective.
\end_layout

